  "body": "## Issue\r\n\r\nThe current HdWallet provider (and similar `provider` options) are automatically initaliazed in truffle.js, causing them to start polling and potentially interfere with environments that they aren't associated with (especially if they output debug logs).\r\n\r\n## Steps to Reproduce\r\n\r\nHave two HD wallet providers (e.g. one pointing at testrpc, one pointing at ropsten.infura), for example (ignore the different api, ).\r\n\r\n```\r\nmodule.exports = {\r\n  networks: {\r\n    ropsten: {\r\n      provider: new HDWalletProvider(seed, 'https://ropsten.infura.io/'),\r\n      network_id: '3',\r\n    },\r\n    test: {\r\n      provider: new HDWalletProvider(seed, 'http://localhost:8545/'),\r\n      network_id: '*',\r\n    },\r\n  },\r\n};\r\n```\r\n\r\n## Expected Behavior\r\n\r\nWhen `truffle migrate --network ropsten` is called, only the Ropsten provider is initialiezed. \r\n\r\n## Actual Results\r\n\r\nBoth providers are initialized, triggering `engine.start()` on both of them, and causing both providers to begin polling (even though only the ropsten provider should be). If the TestRPC isn't isn't available, it throws both migrations. \r\n\r\n## Environment\r\n\r\n* Operating System: osx\r\n* Truffle version: 3.0.4\r\n* Ethereum client: --\r\n* node version: 6.x\r\n* npm version: 3.x\r\n\r\n## Suggested Fix\r\n\r\nHave the provider trigger initialization only when one of it's methods is called (this way you don't need some special 'activation' API).",
